8. No genre or too many genres 

You have to pick one. Your agent needs to know where this will sit on a shelf in a bookstore.

7. Forgetting to say thank you 

Always thank the agent! This is their time too!

6. Neologisms 

The quend is full of foical nodges. In English: the pitch is full of made-up words. It takes up too much room to explain them. Just use plain English; save the made-up words for the book itself.

5. Synopsis, not pitch 

You're giving us a synopsis of the book instead of a pitch, which should roughly summarize the plot but be succinct and leave us hanging at the end.

4. Old comps 

General rules I've heard are past 3 years. Old, super famous stuff isn't helpful because that market is different now.

3. Lonely comps 

Comps without a description of WHY you're using them aren't helpful. The agent wants to know what aspect of your book is similar.

2. Too much meta data 

You need word count, genre, comps. Not a lengthy description of your book's themes and influences.

1. No stakes 

You tell us about the plot, but not what bad thing will happen if they don't succeed...so we don't know why the plot is important
